{"title_page": "Pilgrim's Pride", "text_new": "{{Infobox company\n | name             = Pilgrim's Pride Corporation\n | logo             = Pilgrim's Pride logo.svg\n | type             = [[Public company|Public]]\n | traded_as        = {{NASDAQ|PPC}}<br>[[S&P 400]] component\n | genre            = \n | foundation       = 1946\n | founder          = \n | location_city    = [[Greeley, Colorado]]\n | location_country = [[United States]]\n | location         = \n | locations        = \n | area_served      = \n | key_people       = [[Jayson Penn]] <small>([[CEO]])</small>\n | industry         = [[Meat processing]]\n | products         = [[Food]] and [[beverages]]\n | services         = \n | revenue          = {{profit}} US$ 10.7&nbsp;billion <small>(2017)</small>\n | operating_income = \n | net_income       = {{increase}} US$ 718.1&nbsp;million <small>(2017)</small>\n | assets           = \n | equity           = \n | owner            = [[JBS USA]] (78.5%)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ir.pilgrims.com/secfiling.cfm?filingID=802481-17-26&CIK=802481|title=Pilgrim's Pride Proxy Statement|website=Pilgrims.com|access-date=February 1, 2018}}</ref>\n | num_employees    = 35,700\n | parent           = \n | divisions        = \n | subsid           = [[Moy Park]]\n | caption           = \n | homepage         = {{url|www.pilgrims.com}}\n | footnotes        = \n | intl             = \n}}\n'''Pilgrim's Pride Corporation''' is an American, multi-national food company, currently one of the largest [[chicken]] producers in the United States and [[Puerto Rico]] and the second-largest chicken producer in Mexico.  It exited bankruptcy in December 2009 and relocated its U.S. headquarters to [[Greeley, Colorado]], in 2011.<ref>\"[http://www.pilgrims.com./company/contact-us.aspx Contact Us].\" Pilgrim's Pride. Retrieved on February 3, 2011. \"Pilgrim's Corp. 1770 Promontory Circle Greeley, CO 80634.\"</ref> It is majority-owned by [[JBS S.A.]]. Pilgrim's Pride purchased Gold N'Plump for $350 million in late November 2016.\n\n==Description of firm==\nPilgrim's Pride is a multi-national corporation, based in Brazil, and employs about 38,000 people with sales of $8.1 billion in 2012, and has operations in 12 states, Mexico and Puerto Rico.  They have the capacity to process about 36 million birds per week resulting in almost 9.5 billion pounds of live chicken annually.<ref>http://www.pilgrims.com/company/</ref>\n\nPilgrim's Pride products are distributed primarily through foodservice and retail outlets.\n\nPilgrim's traces its origins to a feed store opened in 1946 in [[Pittsburg, Texas]], by [[Lonnie \"Bo\" Pilgrim]] and his older brother, Aubrey. They were known to give away free chicks with the bags of feed they sold, thereby expanding their business. Bo, wearing traditional [[Pilgrim (Plymouth Colony)|Pilgrim]] garb, with a pet chicken named \"Henrietta\" under his arm, was featured in Pilgrim's Pride advertisements. He became the president of the company after Aubrey died of a heart attack in 1966.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pilgrims.com/our-company/about-us.aspx|title=About Us - Pilgrim's|website=www.Pilgrims.com|access-date=February 1, 2018}}</ref> Today, Pilgrim's Pride is [[vertical integration|vertically integrated]], meaning the company has its own divisions for every process from \"egg to table\".\n\nPilgrim's Pride is a supplier of [[KFC|Kentucky Fried Chicken]] and was named its \"supplier of the year\" in 1997. Other customers include [[Walmart]], [[Publix]], and [[Wendy's]]. By 2012, Pilgrim's was the exclusive [[rotisserie chicken]] supplier for [[Costco]], supplying 50 million 3-pound marinated chickens, ready to be placed into a [[rotisserie]].<ref name=\"wash_Theb\">{{Cite web\n| title = The bird that goes around, stays around\n| author = \n| work = Washington Post\n| date = \n| accessdate = 2018-01-31\n| url = https://www.washingtonpost.com/lifestyle/food/the-bird-that-goes-around-stays-around/2012/10/29/e1509d2c-073c-11e2-a10c-fa5a255a9258_story.html\n| quote = Costco uses a single producer, Pilgrim\u2019s Pride, which marinates via injection, trusses and packs 10 birds to a case. The chickens look like pale, plump ghosts as they get threaded onto long rods that fit in ultra-modern, digital-display Inferno 4000 rotisserie ovens.\n}}</ref>\n\n==News events in the 2000s/2010s==\n[[Image:Pilgrims pride formerlogo.png|thumb|left|150px|Pilgrim's Pride logo used until 2011.]]\nOn October 12, 2002, Pilgrim's Pride recalled 27.4 million pounds of sliced deli poultry after finding a strain of ''[[Listeria monocytogenes]]'' in the drain of one of their facilities. It was the largest [[food recall]] in the US at the time. The outbreak killed 7 people, sickened 46, and caused 3 miscarriages. [http://www.fsis.usda.gov/oa/recalls/prelease/pr090-2002.htm] [http://www.foodproductiondaily.com/news/ng.asp?id=28903-us-inspector-blames] <ref>{{cite news| url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?sec=health&res=9A02E3DF123FF933A05753C1A9649C8B63 | work=The New York Times | title=EATING WELL; Listeria Thrives in a Political Hotbed | first=Marian | last=Burros | date=October 30, 2002 | accessdate=May 22, 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn 2003, Pilgrim's Pride acquired Pierce Chicken (formerly of [[ConAgra Foods]] and Hester Industries). Pierce Chicken is best known for its brand-name Wing Dings, Wing Zings, and various other prepared food products.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.livestockweekly.com/papers/03/06/26/whlconachicken.asp|title= ConAgra Sells Poultry Business|website=LivestockWeekly.com|access-date=February 1, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2004, Pilgrim's Pride experienced an outbreak of [[avian influenza]] in [[Hopkins County, Texas|Hopkins County]] in northeast Texas; 24,000 breeder hens were destroyed to contain the outbreak. [http://www.dec.state.ak.us/eh/vet/alerts.htm]\n\nOn July 20, 2004, [[PETA]] released a video showing cruelty to chickens at a Pilgrim's Pride plant in [[West Virginia]].<ref name=\"2004 PETA\">{{cite news\n|url= https://www.nytimes.com/2004/07/25/weekinreview/the-nation-gaining-ground-at-last-a-company-takes-peta-seriously.html\n|title= The Nation: Gaining Ground; At Last, a Company Takes PETA Seriously\n|accessdate= 2009-07-30\n|date= 2004-07-25\n|newspaper= The New York Times\n| first=Donald G.\n| last=McNeil Jr}}</ref>  The video showed Pilgrim Pride employees kicking, jumping, throwing, and spitting on live chickens.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://money.cnn.com/2004/07/20/news/fortune500/kfc/index.htm | work=CNN | title=Animal cruelty taped at KFC supplier | date=July 20, 2004 | accessdate=May 22, 2010}}</ref>  Pilgrim's Pride held an investigation, fired 11 employees, including managers, and has provided ongoing animal welfare training to its work force after KFC owner [[Yum Brands]] threatened to cease purchasing from the company following the incident; none of the employees faced any criminal charges.\n\nPilgrim's is also a supplier of cattle feed to various ranching operations in East Texas. The supply of cattle feed was criticized because of the alleged use of \"inedible\" chicken parts being used for protein content. This is a common practice in the poultry industry known as protein conversion, so as to profit from all parts of the bird. Protein conversion uses techniques to convert inedible parts of the animal, such as keratin in feathers and skin, into digestible protein to be used for livestock and pet food.\n\nOn December 4, 2006, Pilgrim's Pride announced the successful acquisition [http://phx.corporate-ir.net/phoenix.zhtml?c=68228&p=irol-newsArticle&ID=938229&highlight=] of [[Gold Kist]] (formerly the third largest chicken company) for $21.00 a share.  Although there was initial resistance from Gold Kist, the board members of both companies voted unanimously to combine the two companies.\n\nOn December 17, 2007, Pilgrim's Pride's [[CEO]], O.B. Goolsby, Jr., died after suffering a stroke while on a hunting trip in South Texas with customers.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.reuters.com/article/rbssConsumerGoodsAndRetailNews/idUSN1736015720071217 | work=Reuters | title=UPDATE 2-Pilgrim's Pride CEO dead after stroke | first=Martinne | last=Geller | date=December 17, 2007}}</ref>\n\nOn April 16, 2008, after a yearlong investigation [[US Immigration and Customs Enforcement]] raided plants in [[Batesville, Arkansas]]; [[Live Oak, Florida]]; [[Chattanooga, Tennessee]]; [[Mount Pleasant, Texas]]; and [[Moorefield, West Virginia]]. Officials arrested 311 foreign national employees on suspicion of [[identity theft]]. Of these, 91 have been formally charged.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ice.gov/pi/news/newsreleases/articles/080417dallas.htm|title=pi news newsreleases articles 080417dallas - Immigration and Customs Enforcement (ICE) Search Results|website=www.ICE.gov|access-date=February 1, 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Pittsburg August 2015 10 (Pilgrim's Pride feed mill).jpg|thumb|The Pilgrim's Pride [[feed mill]] in [[Pittsburg, Texas]], in August 2015]]\n\nOn May 27, 2014, the company announced a $6.4 billion cash and debt offer to acquire all the shares in [[Hillshire Brands]]. A rival bid from [[Tyson Foods]] followed two days later. On June 9, 2014, the company announced it was withdrawing its bid for Hillshire after Tyson Foods had increased its offer to $8.55 billion.<ref name=\"WinningBid\">{{cite news|date=May 29, 2014|title=Tyson Foods wins battle to buy Hillshire Brands|url=http://thebostonjournal.com/2014/05/29/tyson-offers-to-buy-hillshire-in-6-8-billion-deal/|access-date=June 10, 2014|newspaper=The Boston Journal|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150529162950/http://thebostonjournal.com/2014/05/29/tyson-offers-to-buy-hillshire-in-6-8-billion-deal/|archivedate=May 29, 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn July 21, 2017, the company's co-founder, Lonnie \"Bo\" Pilgrim, died at the age of 89.<ref>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/obituaries/lonnie-bo-pilgrim-poultry-baron-and-prominent-texas-political-donor-dies-at-89/2017/07/25/2e59cc72-7143-11e7-8f39-eeb7d3a2d304_story.html Lonnie \u2018Bo\u2019 Pilgrim, poultry baron and prominent Texas political donor, dies at 89], by Harrison Smith, in the Washington Post; published July 25, 2017; retrieved August 2, 2017</ref>\n\n==Purchase by JBS S.A.==\n\nOn September 17, 2009, [[JBS USA]] Holdings, Inc. announced the purchase of 64% of the shares of Pilgrim's Pride. JBS USA Holdings, Inc. is a subsidiary of Brazilian multinational [[JBS S.A.]], the largest meat processor in the world, and the largest by revenue. Currently JBS USA Holdings, Inc. owns 78.5% of the company.\n\nAs a result, Pilgrim's Pride closed its corporate offices in Texas and Georgia and moved its headquarters to Greeley, Colorado.<ref>\"[http://www.publicbroadcasting.net/kera/news.newsmain/article/1/0/1635626/North.Texas/Pilgrim%27s.Pride.cutting.213.jobs..and..Nightly.Roundup Pilgrim's Pride cutting 213 jobs & Nightly Roundup].\" ''[[KERA (FM)|KERA]]''. April 12, 2010. Retrieved on February 3, 2011.</ref> This move caused the former headquarters in [[Pittsburg, Texas]], and a location in nearby [[Mt. Pleasant, Texas]], to cut employment by a total of 160 people. Other locations which lost jobs included sites in [[Atlanta]], [[Dallas]], and [[Broadway, Virginia]].<ref>\"[https://www.reuters.com/article/2010/01/05/pilgrimspride-idUSN054358020100105 UPDATE 1-Pilgrim's Pride sets layoffs; integration begins].\" ''[[Reuters]]''. Tuesday January 5, 2010. Retrieved on February 3, 2011.</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=X9wHzt6gBgI | title=Chickens | work=[[Last Week Tonight with John Oliver]] | date=17 May 2015 | accessdate=19 May 2015}}.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Colorado|Companies}}\n* [http://www.pilgrims.com/ Company website]\n* [https://web.archive.org/*/http://www.pilgrimspride.com Pilgrim's Pride website] (Archive)\n* [http://www.poultry.com/ Pilgrim's Pierce Chicken division]\n\n[[Category:JBS]]\n[[Category:Companies listed on NASDAQ]]\n[[Category:Food and drink companies established in 1946]]\n[[Category:Agriculture companies of the United States]]\n[[Category:Economy of Dallas]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Greeley, Colorado]]\n[[Category:Brand name poultry meats]]\n[[Category:Food recalls]]\n[[Category:Camp County, Texas]]\n[[Category:1946 establishments in Texas]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox company\n | name             = Pilgrim's Pride Corporation\n | logo             = Pilgrim's Pride logo.svg\n | type             = [[Public company|Public]]\n | traded_as        = {{NASDAQ|PPC}}<br>[[S&P 400]] component\n | genre            = \n | foundation       = 1946\n | founder          = \n | location_city    = [[Greeley, Colorado]]\n | location_country = [[United States]]\n | location         = \n | locations        = \n | area_served      = \n | key_people       = [[Jayson Penn]] <small>([[CEO]])</small>\n | industry         = [[Meat processing]]\n | products         = [[Food]] and [[beverages]]\n | services         = \n | revenue          = {{profit}} US$ 10.7&nbsp;billion <small>(2017)</small>\n | operating_income = \n | net_income       = {{increase}} US$ 718.1&nbsp;million <small>(2017)</small>\n | assets           = \n | equity           = \n | owner            = [[JBS USA]] (78.5%)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ir.pilgrims.com/secfiling.cfm?filingID=802481-17-26&CIK=802481|title=Pilgrim's Pride Proxy Statement|website=Pilgrims.com|access-date=February 1, 2018}}</ref>\n | num_employees    = 35,700\n | parent           = \n | divisions        = \n | subsid           = [[Moy Park]]\n | caption           = \n | homepage         = {{url|www.pilgrims.com}}\n | footnotes        = \n | intl             = \n}}\n'''Pilgrim's Pride Corporation''', is a American, multi-national food company, currently one of the largest [[chicken]] producers in the United States and [[Puerto Rico]] and the second-largest chicken producer in Mexico.  It exited bankruptcy in De