rly the third largest chicken company) for $21.00 a share.  Although there was initial resistance from Gold Kist, the board members of both companies voted unanimously to combine the two companies.\n\nOn December 17, 2007, Pilgrim's Pride's [[CEO]], O.B. Goolsby, Jr., died after suffering a stroke while on a hunting trip in South Texas with customers.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.reuters.com/article/rbssConsumerGoodsAndRetailNews/idUSN1736015720071217 | work=Reuters | title=UPDATE 2-Pilgrim's Pride CEO dead after stroke | first=Martinne | last=Geller | date=December 17, 2007}}</ref>\n\nOn April 16, 2008, after a yearlong investigation [[US Immigration and Customs Enforcement]] raided plants in [[Batesville, Arkansas]]; [[Live Oak, Florida]]; [[Chattanooga, Tennessee]]; [[Mount Pleasant, Texas]]; and [[Moorefield, West Virginia]]. Officials arrested 311 foreign national employees on suspicion of [[identity theft]]. Of these, 91 have been formally charged.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ice.gov/pi/news/newsreleases/articles/080417dallas.htm|title=pi news newsreleases articles 080417dallas - Immigration and Customs Enforcement (ICE) Search Results|website=www.ICE.gov|access-date=February 1, 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Pittsburg August 2015 10 (Pilgrim's Pride feed mill).jpg|thumb|The Pilgrim's Pride [[feed mill]] in [[Pittsburg, Texas]], in August 2015]]\n\nOn May 27, 2014, the company announced a $6.4 billion cash and debt offer to acquire all the shares in [[Hillshire Brands]]. A rival bid from [[Tyson Foods]] followed two days later. On June 9, 2014, the company announced it was withdrawing its bid for Hillshire after Tyson Foods had increased its offer to $8.55 billion.<ref name=\"WinningBid\">{{cite news|date=May 29, 2014|title=Tyson Foods wins battle to buy Hillshire Brands|url=http://thebostonjournal.com/2014/05/29/tyson-offers-to-buy-hillshire-in-6-8-billion-deal/|access-date=June 10, 2014|newspaper=The Boston Journal|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150529162950/http://thebostonjournal.com/2014/05/29/tyson-offers-to-buy-hillshire-in-6-8-billion-deal/|archivedate=May 29, 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn July 21, 2017, the company's co-founder, Lonnie \"Bo\" Pilgrim, died at the age of 89.<ref>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/obituaries/lonnie-bo-pilgrim-poultry-baron-and-prominent-texas-political-donor-dies-at-89/2017/07/25/2e59cc72-7143-11e7-8f39-eeb7d3a2d304_story.html Lonnie \u2018Bo\u2019 Pilgrim, poultry baron and prominent Texas political donor, dies at 89], by Harrison Smith, in the Washington Post; published July 25, 2017; retrieved August 2, 2017</ref>\n\n==Purchase by JBS S.A.==\n\nOn September 17, 2009, [[JBS USA]] Holdings, Inc. announced the purchase of 64% of the shares of Pilgrim's Pride. JBS USA Holdings, Inc. is a subsidiary of Brazilian multinational [[JBS S.A.]], the largest meat processor in the world, and the largest by revenue. Currently JBS USA Holdings, Inc. owns 78.5% of the company.\n\nAs a result, Pilgrim's Pride closed its corporate offices in Texas and Georgia and moved its headquarters to Greeley, Colorado.<ref>\"[http://www.publicbroadcasting.net/kera/news.newsmain/article/1/0/1635626/North.Texas/Pilgrim%27s.Pride.cutting.213.jobs..and..Nightly.Roundup Pilgrim's Pride cutting 213 jobs & Nightly Roundup].\" ''[[KERA (FM)|KERA]]''. April 12, 2010. Retrieved on February 3, 2011.</ref> This move caused the former headquarters in [[Pittsburg, Texas]], and a location in nearby [[Mt. Pleasant, Texas]], to cut employment by a total of 160 people. Other locations which lost jobs included sites in [[Atlanta]], [[Dallas]], and [[Broadway, Virginia]].<ref>\"[https://www.reuters.com/article/2010/01/05/pilgrimspride-idUSN054358020100105 UPDATE 1-Pilgrim's Pride sets layoffs; integration begins].\" ''[[Reuters]]''. Tuesday January 5, 2010. Retrieved on February 3, 2011.</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=X9wHzt6gBgI | title=Chickens | work=[[Last Week Tonight with John